title: Hand lathe for PTFE bearing / bushing turn down

description.text:
Motivation

I wanted to try solid PTFE bushings (D15mm, d8mm, L10mm) because they offer similar static and dynamic coefficient of friction. This prevents the stick-slip effect which is very pronounced with PLA on hardened steel. However, I couldn't find precisely manufactured PTFE tubes (or hollow poles) on ebay (www.ebay.de/itm//261909054576). Tolerances are quite bad: A D15mm, d8mm tube turned out to be D16.2mm, d7.8mm. So reaming and lathing is mandatory.

This handheld lathe uses a box cutter blade for milling, a 8mm rod as an axis and a cordless screwdriver as a motor. Radius adjustment is done by means of a 16mm M3 screw.

This lathe is not precise. Iterative corrections are required to get the proper outer diameter.

The photos show an older version, which didn't work well. The blade has to be close to perpendicular to the cylindric surface and not close to tangential.

Usage

Put in the rod though the long hole, put on the cut PTFE tube on the rod and finally put the rod though the short hole. Place the PTFE tube close to the short hole. Adjust the desired cutting radius. I suggest not to turn down more than 0.5mm per run. Pull the rod in direction of the long hole to start milling. Keep the rotation speed low and slowly pull the rod. Try which rotation direction (clockwise or counterclockwise) offers the best result. You need to develop experience or a feel for the process to obtain a perfectly smooth outer surface. Yes, a perfectly machined outer surface is possible. :)

Use a reamer or a rough sanded 8mm rod to get the proper inner diameter until no friction occurs.

Notes:

Please select a proper printing orientation by hand.

Mehrel (Orange) - Based on CIH, or the Chernobyl virus. description.text:
This is a remote box to switch 230V with the octoprint/raspberry.
So i can turn the Power for my printer on and off by remote.
The raspbery Pi normaly needs 5W and the Printer needs 10W stantby. (15W standby together)
I had uploadet 2 diverent parts for the body of the case.
One version for the K8200 heatbed upgrade (to set on top of the powersupply) and one universal version.
Inside the box in a relais modul with 2 relais so i can switch both wires.
The switch on the backside can select the mode:
"permanent on" / "off" / "raspi controll".

It uses WiringPi
For installation you will find infos at http://wiringpi.com/download-and-install/ To ad the commands to octopi you must edit the config.yarnl
I had upload the file printerPower2.txt with the modifikation under "system:" For wiring you must remove the jumper at the relaisboard.
(Board like this http://www.sainstore.de/sainsmart-2-kanal-5v-relay-modul-fur-arduino-dsp-avr-pic-arm.html)
RasPi -> Relais board (http://wiringpi.com/pins/)
5V -> JD-VCC
GND -> GND
3V3 -> VCC
GPIO7 -> IN1 & IN2 Parts i had used:
http://www.reichelt.de/Kaltgeraetestecker/KES-3SI/3/index.html?&ACTION=3&LA=2&ARTICLE=9360&GROUPID=5203&artnr=KES+3SI
(Dont forget to order a fuse, it is not includet)

description.text:
This is a baseball bat rattle for your little baseball fans.. but it is more than that! It is also just... well, a bat!

Here's the bat/rattle in action: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MyliVKES1JM

I have designed this bat to be put together without any glues (although they wouldn't hurt). The files I uploaded create an assembled bat that measures about 16" in length. I designed it this way so it can be used as a rattle as well as a small bat to teach toddlers how to hit. I can also be downsized by 1/2 and be a normal sized rattle (roughly 8"), or it can be doubled in size and be a full size (32") wiffle ball bat! If you do decide to make the doubled version:
A. It will require a very large printer (obviously)
B. I recommend using an epoxy to give you extra strength so you can really go for those dingers!

  • Directions -

  1. Print out one of each STL file except for the Peas. I printed out five sets (25) of the peas and that seemed very sufficient for the "rattle sound". Make sure to print out the peas before you print the barrel.

  2. While printing the barrel, pause your print roughly 1/3 of the way through to place the peas inside (I actually did not have any trouble placing the peas during the print, but pausing is probably the safer method). Make sure to check out the photo of this.

Finally, I would like to thank @dutchmogul for inspiring me to create this thing. I made his mace a while back and my son loves it! I'm hoping he will enjoy this bat just as much!

Putting Your Bat Together

  1. Press fit your knob (Bat_Knob.stl) and your handle (Bat_Handle1) together. Add glue if you would like (you shouldn't need it)

  2. Press fit your handle into the taper (Bat_Taper1.stl). Add glue if you would like (you shouldn't need it)

  3. Press fit the taper into the barrel (Bat_Barrell.stl). Add glue if you would like (you shouldn't need it)

  4. Press fit the end cap (Bat_EndCap1.stl) into the barrel. Add glue if you would like (you shouldn't need it)
This was designed using Autodesk Inventor

These need to be printed out of a flex material, I used Sainsmart TPU

I did not love any of the existing solutions out there to reduce vibrations and keep the printer from moving so I created my own. They are low profile and they fit with or without the felt pad on the Y-Axis corners.

Infill doesn't really matter I think mine are 30%
layer height was .15mm, but will be fine at ,2

title: KNK FORCE Plotter Gel Pen Ink Refil Holder Ohuhu

description.text:
This holder is designed to hold Ohuhu Gel Ink refills and then used as a drawing tool in plotters, specifically the KNK Force. It is spring loaded to keep the refill end in contact with paper.

The two halves screw together right off the printer bed. You insert a refill into the bottom half. Find a spring, Pilot G-2 works, and insert over top of refill. If spring is to weak just stretch it out until you have the tension you need, I left this length a little long. Easier to stretch then to compress. Screw on the top.

I found that a little clean up is needed for the tip. Mainly because it is the end that is attached to the bed. You need to stand the parts up in your slicer program. The bottom holder prints from the tip and the top prints from the end. Use a 5mm raft or bigger.

My version of the X-axis belt tensioner for the Anet A6.

It consists of a tensioner, which houses the pulley, and a modified plate. The plate has a cutout that the original does not have, this provides room for the bolt sticking out of the tensioner.
The tensioner uses an existing hole in the right-side panel of the Z-axis housing. I re-used the bolt of the pulley to mount the pulley in my tensioner.

A few notes:
Beware that you put washers on both side of the pulley! This may need some filing away of the plastic. Adding washers ensures that the pulley can move freely.

Also take note of the mounting order (as shown in photos):

  • Pull belt through hole in Z-axis housing
  • Pull belt through tensioner (might need some fiddling :))
  • Put long M3 bolt in tensioner, put a washer behind the head of the bolt.
  • Mount tensioner in Z-axis housing with top and right panel removed
  • Re-mount right panel and then the top panel

To prevent over-tensioning, mount a belt tensioning spring.

comments.text:
The spring is there to prevent over-tensioning. Yes, you should pull the belt tight, but not too tight, the spring prevents this. Tensioning too tight will put unnecessary and excessive wear on the motor and the pulley.
I have no quality problems with the spring in place.
comments.author: McSchweg

comments.text:
The spring can not prevent over tensioning.
In fact, a spring adds an unwanted dynamic element in the drive.
I really recommend only to tighten the belt until it has good tension and leave all other cosmetics like those springs out.
It only adds a false impression of tightness that is overruled by strong fast movements and ringing or overdrawing at corners will be the effects.
If you do not have the problems, you have tightened the belt really well. But then the spring is obsolete and you can get rid of it.
Do your agree?

title: Miniature holder for painting with larger hands

description.text:
See it in action here: https://quik.gopro.com/v/UaBeLvSyMo/
I've been painting miniatures for over 20 years. Most the time, I use a cork or other item to tack or pin the model to. The problem is, with larger hands and over long periods, it causes cramping in my fingers and joints to hold such a small piece. Plus, I never feel like I have a good grip on the model. I created this to eliminate those problems, and also allow me to rotate the model while painting without losing grip.
Suggestions:
-MAKE SURE TO ROTATE SOME PIECES...THEY HAVE INDENTIONS ON BOTTOM!

  • I included a shaft print, but I actually ended up just cutting a 1/4" PVC pipe and using it. It was much easier to shave to correct tightness and didn't use up material.
  • Make sure to glue the turn wheel and top piece without accidentally gluing the main body. Do a check fit and shave to as close as you can. This will give you a nice snug fit and ensure the wheel doesn't turn while you're painting.

  • 2x Serrated lock washer for M4(for one end of the screw = the head of the screw, for another end of the screw = a gap between vertical & horizontal head part)

Handle:
